These hyper-parameters are typically used in existing worksÂ [13, 14, 22, 18, 8].

We also compare the training accuracy when more workers (N=50ğ‘50N=50 and N=100ğ‘100N=100) participate the training to demonstrate the cross-siloed FLÂ [41] (typically up to one hundred participants). The results in Fig.Â 3(d) and (h) show the same trend as results in TableÂ II.

We observe that HierMo >> HierFAVG >> DOMO >> FedADC >> FedNAG >> CFL >> FedMom >> SlowMo >> Mime â‰ˆ\approx FedAvg in most cases. This is consistent with the results in TableÂ II, showing that HierMo outperforms all benchmarks under any levels of non-i.i.d. data distribution.
We also observe higher level of non-i.i.d. setting decreases convergence performance for all algorithms. Specifically, HierMo achieves 66.11% accuracy for high level non-i.i.d. data, while achieving 92.21% accuracy and 94.70% accuracy for middle and low level non-i.i.d. data respectively. This matches our expectations where higher level of non-i.i.d. setting causes more data divergence that is denoted by larger Î´ğ›¿\delta, and therefore lowers the accuracy.
